comments: Published in 1957 in by the Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (now Community of Christ), a Restoration-based denomination in the hymn book "Children's Hymnal". Tune given as "John Bown's Body", but in the very popular Wee Sing series, the tune is given as "Battle Hymn". Both tunes are in fact derived from the traditional "Say Brothers, Will You Meet Us?". The lyrics are inspired by the children's book "The Tale of Peter Rabbit", a children's book written and illustrated by Beatrix Potter in 1902, that follows mischievous and disobedient young Peter Rabbit as he gets into, and is chased around, the garden of Mr. McGregor.

comments: Pasodoble composed in 1927 by the Valencian Manuel Penella for the singer Concha Piquer. The lyrics recount a Christmas Eve celebration of a group of Spanish citizens in New York City during the term of the so-called "Dry Law". It describes how they are able to circumvent the ban by means of a recipe that allows them to buy Spanish wine in a pharmacy. After the toasts and the joy of the celebration, everyone listens to a Spanish pasodoble that plunges them into the nostalgia of the distant homeland. The pasodoble, in question, whose chords are integrated into this theme as a climax is Suspiros de España composed by Antonio Álvarez Alonso

comments: The verse was written by the English poet and Unitarian hymn writer Sarah Flower Adams at her home "Sunnybank", in Loughton, Essex, England, in 1841. It was first set to music by Adams's sister, the composer Eliza Flower, for William Johnson Fox's collection Hymns and Anthems (1845) But in 1859 Sarah Flower Adams' lyrics were set to the tune of Bethany and published in Lowell Mason 's "Sabbath Hymn and Tune Book". which subsequently became the most used tune.
